How do we displace this capacity?<br>
<br>
Lets pick some numbers...<br>
A french 1 gig reactor costs (with capital charges) 2.6 billion dollars. <br>
That means it costs $2.60 to make available 1 watt of power. This does not include the fuel and operating costs, just the construction costs.<br>
<br>
Now, consider the 100 watt lightbulb.<br>
<br>
It costs the utility (actually us), $260 to simply provide enough nuclear powerplant to light that bulb (plus the extra cost of actually making electricity)!<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> <br>
<br>
Uhmmm it's not becuase i doubt your skills in math, but...<br>
<br>
Dividing the price of the plant by the effect, is not how you calqulate the costs.<br>
<br>
What said was not even based on reality , but on both a guess and an abstraction.<br>
<br>
The average nuclear powerplant with construction, running and disposal of waste, according to IAEA costs about 30$ per Megawatt/hour, compared to the coalpowerplants that costs about 29$ per Megawatt/hour.<br>
<br>
What you said would only be true if the plant owners tried to pay the costs of construction, within a second!<br>
