<br>
Power (which I was discussing) is in Kilowatts, megawatts, whatever. This is the basis for capacity construction costs.<br>
<br>
Energy is in kilowatthours, megawatthours, etc., and that is what you are talking about.<br>
<br>
The CAPACITY of a generator is how much power it instantaneously produces.<br>
<br>
If you wish do discuss ENERGY comparisons, then my argument is even stronger.<br>
<br>
Using your figures (which seem to only include O&amp;M + fuel) nuclear or coal energy costs ~$30/megawatthour.<br>
<br>
My CFL example has ZERO operating cost for the 75 watt differential.<br>
<br>
Therefore my alternative is is not greatly better, but INFINITELY better.<br>
<br>
BTW - A good WTG has a capacity factor of about 35%, not 50-70%.<br>
<br>
I personally don't like residential wind turbines that much, unless you are WAY out in the boondocks.<br>
<br>
yale<br>
