<br>
An energy source in the future will need to meet four criteria: Cost effective, safe, reliable, and have minimal environmental impact.<br>
<br>
Coal is definitely cost effective, reliable, and fairly safe.  However, it is far from having minimal environmental impact.  Heavy metals in coal have destroyed the lakes and streams in my area.  Eating more than one fish a month will raise your body's Mercury concentration above the acceptable level.  None of the &quot;clean coal&quot; technologies seem to address this issue; it's possible to do, but far too costly.  I don't think this is an energy source we want to have in the future.<br>
<br>
As a researcher in the fusion sector I can tell you 20 years is way too optimistic.  The physics and engineering issues are immense.  DT fusion requires the breeding of Tritium, so at least one Tritium atom must be created for each one fused.  Although this is theoretically possible using 7Li and other neutron multipliers, this may be impractical to harvest.  This is one of the many issues that I could probably write a whole book on if I wanted to.  We may end up having to go to a DD cycle or D3He which have even higher technical requirements minus the Tritium.  <br>
<br>
I would say we will not have a power producing reactor in around 35 years and this says nothing about the economics which is another issue all together.  Does this mean we should not pursue it?  Of course not.  The benefits are too great.  Just try not to believe the overly optimistic estimates of those plasma physicists. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=orion@nuclearspace>Orion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 7<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(5/7/03 2:58 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm25.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=152.topic&index=16>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Nuclear Energy is the most certain furture source</span><hr size=1> 20 years is theoreticly possible, but 50 is better measure.<br>
<br>
I know of our current status within fusion and i'm also going to make a small fusion reactor within these next few years. However an economicly feasible power generating fusion reactor will require advanced molecular manufacturing nanotechnology.<br>
<br>
Football sized tokamaks and their sisters are not the way forward, there are other fusion concepts out (not CF) which appears more feasible.<br>
<br>
The one i will try to construct is a scaled down version of the fusor, a sperical device for producing nuclear reactions.<br>
<br>
It utilises electrostatic fields from an outer anode-grid to an inner transparent cathode-grid. The field accelerates ions into center where they will collide and a few of them will undergo fusion. The effect is increased by the multipacting of electron around the cathode-grid. This is good small concept and has been proven many times to work, however scaling it to power producing levels are also challenge.<br>
<br>
If you wanna know then check out this site.<br>
